pullRequest.body:
The entire `Algebra.GroupPower` folder is problematic in that it treats `pow` as an advanced subject while the rest of mathlib wants to treat it as a primitive. As such, its existence is an obstacle to developing the theory of `pow` transversally.

This PR scatters the lemmas in `Algebra.GroupPower.Basic` to earlier files and deletes it. Also delete `Algebra.GroupWithZero.Bitwise` whose lemmas are completely deprecated (and hard to rehome).

See #9411 for previous work.

nodes.body: Not sure I like this approach. `Algebra.Group.Basic` is already a big file so why do you want to make it heavier this way? I'd rather have a lighter weight `GroupPower.Basic` that imports `Group.Basic` plus the imports you added to it in this PR.

My reasoning is that definitions that are made at the same time should acquire API at the same time. Currently, `one` and `mul` acquire API very early on, but `pow` lags behind for no particular reason, meaning that people avoid using `pow` because it's somehow "heavier". Similarly, predicates should be made as early as they can be reasonably stated, else people will use the definition rather than the predicate itself (see eg `Even.add_pow_le`, which will be fixed by #11986). Other such pairs of definitions that are equivalent in complexity but whose import weights currently wildly differ are:
* `âˆ…` as a finset and `Finset.univ` 
* `Function.Injective` and `Set.InjOn`
* `{x | âˆƒ y, f y = x}` and `Set.range`
* `âˆƒ k, 2 * k = n` and `Even`. See #11863
* More ambitiously, `Set` and `Finset`

Also `Algebra.Group.Basic` isn't getting any heavier? `Data.Nat.Defs` and `Data.Int.Defs` are all things that could be in Std (and probably will be at some point in the future).

I don't see the connection. I can't replace this lemma by an `ofNat` lemma since the statement depends on the parity.

```suggestion ```
Is this then not zpow_ne_zero_of_ne_zero with different argument order?
Sure, but I didn't add this lemma here

These can easily avoid `convert` with respectively
```
  rw [zpow_ofNat, pow_one]
  rw [zpow_ofNat, pow_two]
```

```suggestion
import Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Basic
import Mathlib.Algebra.Group.Commute.Defs
```
And then you can restore these
Is bit0 even involved anywhere now?
Ditto
